                    "typefaceStyle": ["Sans serif", "Serif"],
                    "copy": "# A Date With Elvis\nShould you weary of automobile obsessions or hunger for some Mexican food, head into Main Street’s quirky Azteca Restaurant. Inside, an American antiques decor battles with manager J.J. Jauregui Jr.’s prized collection of Elvis memorabilia, which spills over from the adjacent bar, the Crooner’s Lounge.\n\nOn August 18 visitors to the Garden Grove car show will be serenaded by Elvis impersonators in celebration of the anniversary of the King’s death. A similar event occurs in January, the month of Presley’s birth.\nJauregui expects a crowd of 2,000, and he plans to keep everyone guessing. “For one show, we’ll have a young gold lamé Elvis; for another, a Las Vegas–style jumpsuit Elvis,” he says. “My Elvis manager has 20 or 30 Elvises, so this year we might do a sing-off.”\nOn display inside Azteca will be Jauregui’s acquisitions from last October’s Elvis auction in Las Vegas: a Happy Easter telegram from Elvis’s manager, Col. Tom Parker, to the legendary family and letters to Parker from Sammy Davis Jr. and Cecil B. DeMille. Fans can also behold his limited-edition, Elvis-etched CD Wurlitzer jukebox.\nBut the crowning glory will be parked in front of the restaurant—Jauregui’s 1972 front-wheel-drive 8.2-liter Eldorado convertible, complete with vanity plates that read JLVELVS...",
